{{unreferenced|date=March 2010}} {{Infobox song contest entry | song = {{flagicon|Spain}} "Canta y sé feliz" | image = | caption = | year = 1974 | country = Spain | artist = [[Peret]] | as = | with = | language = Spanish | languages = | composer = [[Peret|Pedro Pubill Calaf]] | lyricist = Pedro Pubill Calaf | conductor = Rafael de Ibarbia Serra | place = 9th | points = 10 | lyrics = [http://www.diggiloo.net/?1974es from Diggiloo Thrush] | clip = | prev = Eres tú | prev_link = Eres tú (Mocedades song) | next = Tú volverás | next_link = Tú volverás }}
'''"Canta y sé feliz"''' ({{IPA-es|ˈkanta i ˈse feˈliθ}}, {{lang|en|"Sing and Be Happy"}}) was the [[Spain|Spanish]] entry to the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1974]] in [[Brighton]], [[United Kingdom]]. It was sung in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] by [[Peret]].
The song is an up-tempo belonging to the [[Catalan rumba]] genre, with both music and lyrics by Pedro Pubill Calaf - Peret himself.
On the night of the final, the song performed in the third position, following [[United Kingdom]]'s [[Olivia Newton-John]] singing "[[Long Live Love (Olivia Newton-John song)|Long Live Love]]" and preceding [[Norway]]'s [[Anne-Karine Strøm]] with "[[The First Day of Love]]", and at the close of the voting had received 10 points, placing 9th in a field of 17.
It was succeeded as [[Spain in the Eurovision Song Contest|Spanish representative]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1975|1975 contest]] by [[Sergio y Estíbaliz]] with "[[Tú volverás]]
