{{Expand French|Chemin de fer Lausanne-Échallens-Bercher|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox rail line |box_width = |native_name = Chemin de fer Lausanne-Échallens-Bercher |native_name_lang = fr |color = |logo = Logo LEB 2017.svg |logo_width = |image = Bercher 2005-09-23.jpg |image_width = 300px |caption = |type = [[narrow gauge]] [[commuter rail]] |system = |status = |locale = [[Vaud]] |start = [[Lausanne-Flon station|Lausanne-Flon]] |end = [[Bercher railway station|Bercher]] |stations = 21 |routes = |daily_ridership = |open = 4 November 1873 |close = |owner = |operator = |character = |depot = |stock = |linelength = |tracklength = {{convert|23.67|km|abbr=on}} |tracks = |gauge = {{RailGauge|1000mm}} |minradius = |electrification = 1500 V DC |maxincline = 6% |racksystem = |speed = |elevation = |map = {{Lausanne–Echallens–Bercher railway}} |map_name = Route diagram |map_state = collapsed |website = http://www.leb.ch }} The '''Lausanne–Echallens–Bercher Railway''' ({{lang-fr|Chemin de fer Lausanne-Échallens-Bercher}}, LEB) is a [[metre gauge]] railway in the [[canton of Vaud]] in [[Switzerland]]. The line connects the city of [[Lausanne]] with [[Bercher]] via [[Echallens]], and is {{convert|23.67|km|abbr=on}} long.
== History == [[File:LEB Company Logo - La ligne verte.svg|thumb|left|Old logo.]]
After an initial test train ran between [[Lausanne-Chauderon station]] and Prilly-Chasseur on 3 October 1873, the first section of line came into service from Lausanne to Cheseaux on 4 November. The line through to Échallens opened in June 1874. Under a legally separate entity, the route to Bercher was completed and opened on 28 November 1889.
At the Lausanne end of the line, developments came later. Chauderon station was moved underground and the original station [[demolition|razed]] in 1995. Trains continued to terminate at Chauderon until 2000, when an extension to [[Lausanne-Flon station]] opened, permitting interchange with the [[Lausanne Métro]].
== Future == Together, the railway company, the canton, and the city of Lausanne have plans to upgrade the line to permit more frequent trains. Building of a new [[double track]] tunnel between [[Lausanne-Chauderon station|Chauderon]] and Montétan stations is expected to take place by 2022, permitting up to 8 trains to run per hour in each direction on the urban section as far as Cheseaux-sur-Lausanne.<ref name="LausanneLEB">{{cite web|url=http://www.lausanne.ch/lausanne-en-bref/lausanne-demain/mobilite/autres-projets/leb.html|title=le LEB - Site officiel de la Ville de Lausanne|publisher=City of Lausanne|accessdate=2014-08-13}}</ref>
